a=-2\sqrt{b^2+c^2}
\sqrt{b^2+c^2} > 0
\implies\sqrt{b^2+c^2}=-\frac a2=2, \alpha=3\theta=60^\circ
\alpha=180^\circ-\theta=160^\circ
\sin\alpha=\frac b{\sqrt{b^2+c^2}}=\frac{\sqrt3}2\implies \alpha=60^\circ
c=\cos\alpha\cdot \sqrt{b^2+c^2}=\frac12\cdot 2=1
